  "tutor_notes": {
    "block1_script": "Pirate, division is like being the fairest captain on the seven seas — everyone gets an equal share of the treasure! When you divide 12 cherries into 3 baskets, you're making sure each basket gets exactly 4. No one gets more, no one gets less. That's the magic of division — perfect fairness every time.",
    "block2_hint": "If you're stuck on 18 ÷ 3, try thinking: 'How many groups of 3 fit into 18?' You can even use your fingers — count by 3s until you reach 18. Each time you count, that's one group!",
    "block3_tips": [
      "Draw circles for each group and fill them one by one — like dealing cards to players",
      "Skip count backwards from the big number by the small number until you reach zero",
      "Remember your multiplication facts backwards — if 4 × 3 = 12, then 12 ÷ 3 = 4"
    ],
    "block5_abstraction": "Division is the superpower of equal sharing. When you master it, you can split any amount into perfect groups — whether it's candy between friends, time between activities, or treasure between pirates. The Blade of Light represents this power: one swift calculation, and everything is divided fairly. In the real world, division helps us share resources, plan schedules, and make sure everyone gets their fair part. It's math that creates fairness and balance in the world.",
    "weak_point_focus": "If Pirate struggles with larger divisions like 30 ÷ 5, go back to visual models. Use the drag_drop mechanic from Stage 1 with bigger numbers — let them physically see 30 items going into 5 groups. Once the pattern clicks visually, the abstract numbers will make sense. Division is sharing, and sharing is something every kid understands when they can see it happen."
  }
